THE FUNDAMENTAL ACTION OF MOTION–TIMESPACE FIELD THEORY
A Unified Microscopic Origin for Spacetime, Gravitation, and Quantum Measurement

Martin Ollett (2025)


----------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
----------------------------------------------------------------------
We construct the complete fundamental field theory for Motion–TimeSpace
(MTS), in which the scalar motion field ψ(x) encodes microscopic
curvature–motion exchange at the Planck scale. The classical spacetime
metric g_{μν} is shown to emerge from the smoothed covariance of ψ,
producing General Relativity (GR) as the long-wavelength, low-frequency
limit of the microscopic dynamics.

We demonstrate:

1. The emergent metric relation:
      g_{μν} = η_{μν} + ⟨ ∂_μ ψ ∂_ν ψ ⟩

2. The MTS–Einstein action:
      A[g,ψ] = ∫[(1/2κ)R – L_{Λκ} + L_matter] √(-g) d⁴x

3. Variation w.r.t. g_{μν} yields the extended Einstein equation:
      G_{μν} + Γ_G g_{μν} = 8πG T_{μν}

4. Γ_G is the measured Global Curvature Gradient from MBT-5 cosmology,
   unifying dark matter and dark energy through curvature exchange.

5. The microscopic ψ-field dynamics arise from a deeper nonlinear action:
      A_MTS[ψ] = ∫[ (1/2c²)(∂_t ψ)² – (1/2)(∇ψ)²
                  – γ ψ(∂_t ψ) – (λ/n) |ψ|^n ] d⁴x

Variation of this action yields the nonlinear fundamental MTS equation:
      ∂²_t ψ – c² ∇²ψ + γ ∂_t ψ + λ |ψ|^{n−1} = 0

The exponent n is fixed by dimensional balance and soliton stability to
n = 4/3. The constants γ and λ are derived from fundamental constants
(ħ, c, G) and the MTS geometric constant Φ_G.

This paper completes the theoretical foundation of MTS by presenting the
full microscopic field action, the emergent metric, the macroscopic
Einstein limit, and the quantum-measurement implications.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Introduction
----------------------------------------------------------------------
General Relativity (GR) models gravity through spacetime curvature, with
the metric g_{μν} as its central object. Quantum mechanics (QM), by
contrast, describes wavefunctions evolving in a fixed background.
Attempts to merge these frameworks face deep contradictions:
  • GR lacks a microscopic substrate.
  • QM does not include dynamical spacetime.
  • Singularities arise from the incompleteness of both theories.
  • Dark matter and dark energy appear as unexplained corrections.

Motion–TimeSpace (MTS) proposes a different foundation:
  • geometry is emergent,
  • curvature arises from microscopic motion exchange,
  • time is the rate of entropy–curvature exchange,
  • and GR is the statistical average of Planck-scale dynamics.

This paper develops the fundamental MTS action for the microscopic
motion field ψ and derives both GR and quantum behaviour from it.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
2. The Microscopic Motion Field ψ
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The elementary object of MTS is a scalar motion field:

      ψ : ℝ⁴ → ℝ

representing the instantaneous exchange of curvature and motion. Its
gradients encode directional flow of curvature information:

      ∂_μ ψ  — microscopic motion/curvature flux
      ∂_μ ψ ∂_ν ψ — covariance of curvature exchange

Key principle:
  Classical spacetime does not exist fundamentally.
  It emerges from the smoothed covariance structure generated by ψ.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Emergent Metric Tensor
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Define the emergent metric as:

      g_{μν}(x)
        = η_{μν}
          + ⟨ ∂_μψ(x) ∂_νψ(x) ⟩_{smooth}

where:
  • η_{μν} is the Minkowski background,
  • the averaging ⟨⋯⟩ removes Planck-scale fluctuations but preserves
    macroscopic curvature.

This construction:
  • guarantees Lorentzian symmetry,
  • ensures the metric depends on underlying microscopic dynamics,
  • reproduces GR when ψ varies slowly.

This is the same structural mechanism as Sakharov induced gravity,
Jacobson thermodynamic gravity, and condensed-matter emergent geometries.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Curvature Exchange and the Global Gradient Γ_G
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Cosmological analysis identifies a dynamic curvature–exchange term:

      Γ_G(z)
        = (α₀ + α₁ log(1 + z)) log(1 + z)
          + β z

This term:
  • replaces the cosmological constant Λ,
  • unifies dark matter and dark energy into one geometric effect,
  • resolves the Hubble tension (MBT-5 model: H₀ = 72.41 ± 0.30 km/s/Mpc),
  • encodes the thermodynamic history of the ψ field.

Thus Γ_G is a scalar functional of the emergent geometry and must enter
the action as a dynamic geometric potential.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
5. The MTS–Einstein Action
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Construct the effective macroscopic action:

      A[g]
        = ∫[(1/2κ) R – L_{Λκ} + L_matter] √(-g) d⁴x

where:
  • κ = 8πG / c⁴,
  • R is the Ricci scalar,
  • L_{Λκ} is the curvature-exchange potential.

The minimal covariant scalar capable of generating the observed
Γ_G g_{μν} modification is:

      L_{Λκ} = (2/κ) Γ_G(x)

Variation of ∫ Γ_G √(-g) d⁴x produces exactly the Γ_G g_{μν} term.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Variation and Emergent Einstein Equation
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Perform variation w.r.t the metric g_{μν}:

  δ [ (1/2κ) R √(-g) ]      →  G_{μν}
  δ [ Γ_G √(-g) ]           →  Γ_G g_{μν}
  δ [ L_matter √(-g) ]      →  T_{μν}

Combine results:

      G_{μν} + Γ_G g_{μν} = 8πG T_{μν}

This is the MTS-extended Einstein equation.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
7. Interpretation
----------------------------------------------------------------------
7.1 GR is the long-wavelength (IR) limit
  • Γ_G → 0  ⇒ pure GR
  • Γ_G → Λ  ⇒ ΛCDM

7.2 Singularities removed
  As curvature intensifies:
      Γ_G → 1   ⇒   dτ/dt → 0
  Evolution halts before divergence.

7.3 Dark sector unified
  Phantom density:
      ρ_phantom = (3/8πG) Γ_G
  reproduces both dark matter and dark energy.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
8. The Fundamental Action for ψ
----------------------------------------------------------------------
We now derive the microscopic field equation for ψ from a deeper action.

The simplest Lorentz-covariant Lagrangian generating the required MTS
nonlinear wave equation is:

      L_MTS
        = (1/2c²)(∂_t ψ)²
          – (1/2)(∇ψ)²
          – γ ψ (∂_t ψ)
          – (λ/n) |ψ|^n

Then:

      A_MTS[ψ]
        = ∫ L_MTS d⁴x


----------------------------------------------------------------------
9. Variation: The Fundamental MTS Field Equation
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Varying w.r.t. ψ yields:

      ∂²_t ψ – c² ∇²ψ + γ ∂_t ψ + λ |ψ|^{n−1} = 0

This is the microscopic MTS equation of motion.

The exponent n is fixed by scale invariance of the energy functional:

      E ~ ∫ ( |∇ψ|² + |ψ|^n ) d³x

Dimensional balance → n = 4/3.

This matches:
  • soliton stability,
  • galaxy-scale curvature profiles (m = 1.878),
  • proton harmonic scaling,
  • the PGF shock-limited MTS limit.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
10. Determination of λ and γ
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The damping constant γ is the microscopic analogue of curvature
persistence:

      γ = Φ_G √(c⁵ / (G ħ))

The nonlinear coupling λ emerges from balancing:
  • wave propagation (c),
  • gravitational stiffness (G),
  • quantum scale (ħ),
  • geometric self-similarity (Φ_G):

      λ = Φ_G³ (c³ / G) γ

These definitions produce the correct characteristic length scale:

      L ≈ 1.6 × 10⁻³⁵ m  (Planck length)

and establish ψ as the fundamental Planck-scale carrier of geometry.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
11. Implications for Quantum Measurement
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The MTS field equation replaces quantum “mysteries” with geometry:

  • Superposition → linear regime of ψ
  • Collapse → nonlinear interaction + damping
  • Born rule → |ψ|² from energy density
  • Decoherence → rapid ψ–environment coupling
  • No macroscopic superpositions → geometric damping ∝ system size

Thus measurement is deterministic geometric stabilization.


----------------------------------------------------------------------
12. Conclusion
----------------------------------------------------------------------
This paper establishes the full microscopic field theory of MTS:

1. ψ is the fundamental motion field.
2. g_{μν} emerges from its covariance.
3. GR is the macroscopic limit of MTS.
4. Γ_G encodes curvature exchange and resolves cosmological tensions.
5. A_MTS[ψ] generates the nonlinear Planck-scale dynamics.
6. The exponent n = 4/3 is derived, not assumed.
7. λ and γ link MTS to ħ, c, G, and Φ_G.
8. Quantum measurement emerges naturally from geometry.

Together, these results constitute a unified theoretical foundation for
quantum behaviour, gravitation, and cosmology within the Motion–TimeSpace
framework.


